Hilal Browser: drop libwebrtc goog_cc_scream_network_controller on Windows

Mozilla's recursive_make backend on Windows fails to resolve the .obj
file for third_party/libwebrtc/modules/congestion_controller/
goog_cc_scream_network_controller/goog_cc_scream_network_controller_gn
when xul.dll is linked, producing:

  No rule to make target '...goog_cc_scream_network_controller.obj',
  needed by '../../../dist/bin/xul.dll'.

The .obj is produced correctly by the compile tier and is reachable by
absolute path on disk, but mozmake reports it missing during the link
step regardless of UNIFIED_SOURCES, FILES_PER_UNIFIED_FILE or clobber
state. This appears to be a path-handling defect specific to this
particular long path in mozmake on Windows.

GoogCcScreamNetworkController is a field-trial-gated experiment that is
only ever instantiated when both rfc_8888_feedback_negotiated is true
and the field trial selects kScreamAfterCe or kGoogCcWithEct1. The
default fallback already in place is GoogCcNetworkController, which is
what regular Firefox WebRTC traffic uses today.

To unblock the Windows build, drop the gn directory from the libwebrtc
DIRS list and stop instantiating GoogCcScreamNetworkController from
goog_cc_factory.cc. Behaviour for the default WebRTC code path is
unchanged; the SCReAM-after-CE and GoogCC-with-ECT1 experimental modes
fall back to GoogCcNetworkController on every platform for consistency.

